# Build System & Toolchain

## Cross Compilation

- Use a cross-compiler toolchain (e.g., `x86_64-elf-gcc`, `aarch64-none-elf-gcc`) — never build kernel code with the host compiler
- Provide a custom linker script (`.ld`) for each target architecture to define memory layout, entry point, and section placement

## ISO / Bootable Image

- The build should produce a bootable ISO via `grub-mkrescue` or `xorriso` for x86 targets
- ARM targets should produce a raw binary or U-Boot image
- Add a `make iso` / `make image` target that builds the final bootable artifact

## QEMU Testing

- Provide `make run-x86`, `make run-x86_64`, `make run-arm` targets that launch QEMU with the correct machine flags
- Use `-serial stdio` so kernel serial output is visible in the terminal
- Use `-no-reboot -no-shutdown` during development so panics don't silently restart

## Linker Script Conventions

- `.text` section first, aligned to page boundary
- `.rodata` after `.text`, read-only
- `.data` and `.bss` last, with `__bss_start` / `__bss_end` symbols exported for zeroing in `_start`
